<H2><U>
Native American Legends About Spiders
</u></H2>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.firstpeople.us/FP-Html-Legends/The-Spider-And-The-People-Osage.html
">Osage Spider Story</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Osage Indian legend about the importance of the spider. 
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><B><A HREF="
http://www.firstpeople.us/FP-Html-Legends/TheSpiderWomanandtheTwins-Hopi.html
">The Spider Woman and the Twins</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Hopi legend about the birth of Spider Grandmother and her first creations.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><B><A HREF="
http://www.indigenouspeople.net/spiderro.htm
">The Story of Spider Rock</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Legends about the Navajo Indian goddess Spider Woman teaching the people to weave and rescuing a lost Navajo boy.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.ourvoices.ca/index/ourvoices-story-action/id.0024
">Legend of Ehep</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Cree Spider legend about the first people being lowered to earth on a web.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.nativeamericanembassy.net/www.lenni-lenape.com/www/html/LenapeArchives/LenapeSet-01/spider.html
">A Spider Myth</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Lenape legend about the origin of spiders. (We suspect that this is not actually a traditional Lenape story<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
at all, but actually a Lenape retelling of the Greek myth of Arachne. Nonetheless it is a nice story.)
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"  ALT="*"><b><A HREF="
http://newkeeperofstories.com/stories/2009/01/28/achomawi-myth/
">The Spider Twins</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Achumawi story about a family of spiders helping the animals to end winter.
<BR>


<H2><U>
Recommended Books of Spider Stories from Native American Myth and Legend
</u><BR><font size=2>Our organization earns a commission from any book bought through these links</font>
</u></H2>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0590461567/natilangofthe-20
">The Magic of Spider Woman</A></B>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
A lovely picture book based on Navajo legends about Spider Woman and the art of rug weaving.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/087358936X/natilangofthe-20
">Spider Spins A Story</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Beautiful children's book presenting Native American spider tales from many tribes.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0873586948/natilangofthe-20
">Grandmother Spider Brings The Sun</A></B>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Another nice children's book illustrating the Cherokee legend of how Spider brought daylight to the world.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0595150179/natilangofthe-20
">Insect Mythology</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Interesting book on the meaning of insects and spiders in world mythology, including Native North America and Mesoamerica.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0452276500/natilangofthe-20
">Spirits of the Earth: A Guide to Native American Nature Symbols, Stories, and Ceremonies</A></B>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Book by a Karuk elder about the meanings of Indian animal spirits, including a chapter on spiders.
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1555911277/natilangofthe-20
">Native American Animal Stories</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Great collection of American Indian folklore about spiders and other animals, told by Abenaki storyteller Joseph Bruchac. 
<BR>

<IMG SRC="dot5.gif"><b><A HREF="
http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0140277714/natilangofthe-20
">American Indian Trickster Tales</a>:</b><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Compilation of more than a hundred Spider Man and other trickster folktales from many different tribes.<BR>
Use discretion sharing these with kids as some of the stories contain adult humor.
<BR>




